Comment: Going into this game, I didn't know what to expect from white.  Looking at white's (short) game history, he looked like a ~1300 player, but it's hard to tell with the opponents he was playing.
I did my usual king's pawn response.
White plunges into main line Sicilian.
To me, this is a weak move, but a lot of folks seem to like it.  I prefer c3.
To me, this is a weak move, but a lot of folks seem to like it.  I prefer c3.
Chase the queen a little.
Good place to hide the queen, except for the king/rook/queen fork it creates on c2.

I though long and hard about this move.  I was *really* tempted to play either Nb4 or Qa5  in an attempt to get that king/queen fork, but in the end I decided that any strategy that relies on my opponent making a mistake is a bad strategy.  Instead, I cautiously fall back into king's indian.  I lead with the knight instead of the queen's pawn because e5 is met with Ng4, costing white the pawn.
White prepares to fianchetto the dark bishop.

I had origianlly intended to play d6, but I had been expecting more direct pressure from white.  Since white's last move was non-aggressive, it left me some room to play.  I decided to challenge white for the center.
Another weak move.  As I noted before, it loses the pawn to Ng4.
After 7. Qe2 Nxe5, I'm left in control of the center.  White is also left with his queen in front of his king on a half open file...
Another weak move.  Not only is it not a pin, but it's reversible.
Another weak move.  Not only is it not a pin, but it's reversible.
Another weak move.  Not only is it not a pin, but it's reversible.

Now the white bishop is in jeopardy, my knight's of out reach of a pin, and I'm lined up for e5.  I did screw up the king's indian, but I had already strayed from that path when I saw that I could take the center.
Predictable.  Again white prepared to fianchetto the bishop.
I now own the center, and the bishop is forced to flee.  Time to look towards castling.
White retreats to a defensive stance.
I now challenge both the white queen and Nxc2 .
White falls back and protects c2.
I bring additional pressure to the c2 square.  Play should continue 12. Bd3 e4 13. Be2 e3 14. fxe3 Nxc2  15. Kf2 Nxa1
However, white failed to see the danger.
